Kerry Skarbakka's performance-based photographic work depicting existential anxieties and loss of control through the acts of falling: https://t.co/i9CCkScqZ3 https://t.co/zzNMXTn39e
Anup Shah received his first assigment for 'National Geographic' magazine in 2001: https://t.co/UmOZX99XJJ https://t.co/IP8WRCQAcs
In 1992 Mark Seliger became chief photographer for Rolling Stone magazine, and during his 10 year tenure shot over 125 covers: https://t.co/jinAQKcOjG https://t.co/vkYFIJIZXA
Norman Seeff established an idiosyncratic photographic practice that sought to reveal the creative process behind his sitter's fame: https://t.co/IslgGd5UoP https://t.co/7uOPG7HlbL
From creator of poetic images to compelling storyteller, Jerry Schatzberg has excelled in both the realms of photography and filmmaking: https://t.co/2HQl4dvhEg https://t.co/OqNGQ5KDzP
Jurgen Schadeberg's photographic work focused particularly on South Africa, where he documented effects of apartheid: https://t.co/6T9fFgFGOe https://t.co/RahUznshUb
Mick Rock first met David Bowie in 1972 and shot some of the most memorable pictures of him as Ziggy Stardust: https://t.co/0pKEwrWYKE https://t.co/FaNcxasXBn
Sarah Quill has spent decades photographing the architecture and way of life in the city of Venice: https://t.co/1hxpHZVLJn https://t.co/unDzwfKSoJ
Herbert Ponting was personally chosen by Captain Scott as the official photographer for his famed expedition to the Antarctic in 1910: https://t.co/sQD460ckqQ https://t.co/0JWTPawsXk

Inspired by his interest in how technology influences our lives, Matthew Pillsbury set about photographing friends and family using computers and watching television in their apartments in his series 'Screen Lives': https://t.co/UJs5CCoh9H https://t.co/f3WLEBB6Xs
Christopher Payne is an American photographer known for his large-format surveys of industry, craft and construction: https://t.co/dUA9xAVd2B https://t.co/8zIGBGdrEx
Norman Parkinson brought fashion photography out of the studio and onto the street, bringing a new kinetic and joyful energy to the genre: https://t.co/jqLycXE6Pk https://t.co/EgXkOmKksG
Terry O'Neill achieved huge success throughout his career, with his work appearing in 'Look', 'Vogue', 'Paris Match' and 'Rolling Stone' magazine: https://t.co/l7pIcg8IZF https://t.co/x1OQHEdmIB
Portia Munson’s work explores themes including life, death, nature, colour and how these interweave and relate to each other: https://t.co/36vSmFfsTk https://t.co/jmbaIvLgDT
Vincent Munier uses a subtle and restrained tonal range in his images, and is particularly interested in form and composition: https://t.co/1FxoMxDoAL https://t.co/5BlnxhwQdg
Social and political issues have always stood at the heart of Filippo Minelli's oeuvre, and he is inspired by ideas of demonstration and protest: https://t.co/lqnX1FxzMm https://t.co/Zd1D8nwyjY
Tony McGee was just 16 when he shot his first cover for Harper's Bazaar magazine: https://t.co/3OIuahy2Wf https://t.co/OqUJDn1xik
Steve McCurry has travelled extensively throughout his career, often returning to India to photograph its landscapes, people and culture: https://t.co/KDg2NWGHXT https://t.co/DJ7SHkDtZ7
Gered Mankowitz accompanied the Rolling Stones on their 1965 tour of the United States: https://t.co/fDGuCwB36Y https://t.co/tbWv5rGHiI
Alex Maclean's aerial photography is chiefly concerned with mapping development and human impact on our environment: https://t.co/y5htzyYKyn https://t.co/BqyJrDldy6
Patrick Lichfield first met the legendary editor of American Vogue, Diana Vreeland, in 1967: https://t.co/sA3H0dzKs4 https://t.co/xPDyqXEBYH

Douglas Kirkland is best known for A Night To Remember the famous photoshoot he took of Marilyn Monroe posing naked in bed in which he created a portfolio of over 50 photographs of her looking relaxed, happy and at ease: https://t.co/q4TL2dxEKK https://t.co/kCWR3Md8Ky

Given the date letter for 1809 on the @WoolleyWallis entrée dish, it seems likely that the object was retailed by the unfortunate John II in the year after his father's death.
John II's business failure brought to an end the Keenes' involvement in the Dublin trade that had started over 50 years earlier when his uncle William was apprenticed to Isaac D'Olier.
John II's tenure at 67 Dame street was short. He was adjudicated bankrupt in 1816 and his lease and the contents of his shop were sold.
In 1783, John Keene took over the shop his brother Arthur had opened in 1775 at 67 Dame street. John died in 1808 and the business passed to his son, also called John.
The Keene brothers were connected through their paternal aunt to the D'Olier family, a connection that gave them their start in the Dublin goldsmiths' trade.

In addition to #LeBas maker's mark, the dish has the mark of John Keene.

As a tight-rope walker, what was Saunders's social status in Georgian society? Is it surprising that he married the daughter of a prominent and prosperous Dublin goldsmith? What life would have been like for Mary, moving from Cork Hill to circus life?

Mary's married life with Saunders appears to have been short. By 1786, he was recorded as married to another woman, Lucy (or Julia) Pinto. She also had a Dublin connection. Her father had been leader of the Smock Alley band from 1773 to 1779.
This contemporary image (from the V&A collection) shows Saunders in full swing. https://t.co/qLHcGxuZFQ

and perform 'a continual Summerset on the Wire, while fireworks are playing from different parts of his body' (Highfill et al, A Biographical Dictionary (1991)). There are records of performances by Saunders in Dublin.

In 1781, a notice announced that, among other feats,  Saunders would stand on his head on a drinking glass with the wire in full swing, balance a French horn on his lips, sound a minuet without using his hands...

Mary's husband had an unusual occupation. The Freeman's Journal described him as 'Mr. Saunders, the celebrated Equilibrist' and the sources show that he was probably the most famous slack- and tight-rope walker in late 18C England.

It is likely that Mary was the daughter of William Wilson and his wife Elizabeth. Wilson had a large shop at Cork Hill (FitzGerald, Silver in Georgian Dublin, pp 61-4). He had been master of the Goldsmiths' Company in 1758-9. #DublinSilver

On 24 March 1764 at St Peter's Aungier street, Dublin,  a young woman called Mary Wilson (who was probably only 16 years old) married Samuel Saunders. The Freeman's Journal noted that the bride was 'the Daughter of Mr. Wilson, Goldsmith of Dame-street'.
